const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "What is the Java coffee variety?",
    a: "Java is an Arabica variety with a Typica lineage that traces back to an Ethiopian landrace, often labeled Abyssinia in older records. It traveled to the island of Java in Indonesia, then to Cameroon, where it was selected for tolerance to coffee berry disease, and finally into Central America. The plant is tall, with elongated cherries and beans, and it is valued for a clean, structured cup with gentle florals and an herbal lift. El Quetzal grows it as Javanica in Nicaragua's Matagalpa highlands, and it is the farm's flagship lot."
  },
  {
    q: "What does washed Java green coffee taste like?",
    a: "Washed Java cups clean and structured rather than loud. Expect a medium body, soft sweetness, and a distinctive herbal or juniper-like note that El Quetzal calls out on the roasted version. There is gentle floral lift and a citric edge at higher altitude, with none of the heavy fruit you get from natural or anaerobic processing. It is a coffee that rewards careful roasting and a clean brew method, which is why it works as both a single origin filter offering and a structured espresso base."
  },
  {
    q: "Is washed Java the same as Anaerobic Java?",
    a: "It is the same variety grown on the same farm, processed two different ways. The washed Java is fermented and rinsed in the traditional manner, which keeps the cup clean and lets the variety and terroir show through. The Anaerobic Java goes through a sealed, oxygen-free fermentation that builds bigger fruit and panela sweetness on top of the same base. Roasters often carry both to show customers how process changes a single coffee. See the Anaerobic Java guide for that side of the lot."
  },
  {
    q: "Where can I buy Java green coffee beans wholesale?",
    a: "El Quetzal Coffee Co. sells farm-direct washed Java green coffee at elquetzal.coffee, in sample packs and full lots, with traceability from tree to export through the farm's own Beneficio San Miguel mill. Because it is the farm's flagship lot, washed Java is more consistently available than the smaller microlots, which makes it a good anchor origin for a wholesale program. Contact El Quetzal directly for current harvest inventory and forward contract options."
  },
  {
    q: "How should I roast washed Java green coffee?",
    a: "Washed Java is versatile across the light to medium range. For a filter offering, a City to City+ roast preserves the herbal lift and citric clarity. For espresso or a flagship house coffee, taking it to a developed medium builds body and sweetness while keeping the structure intact. Avoid pushing into dark roast territory, which flattens the juniper and floral character that makes the lot distinctive. A 19 to 22 percent development ratio is a reasonable starting point for most drum roasters."
  }
];

